The eleven-year conflict involving the Mende ethnic group was the Sierra Leone Civil War, which lasted from 1991 to 2002. The Mende were heavily involved through the Kamajors, a group of traditional hunters who formed much of the Civil Defence Forces fighting alongside the government against rebel factions like the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) and Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC). The conflict was caused by political instability, control over diamond resources, and rebel insurgency. It severely impacted the Mende community, leading to loss of lives and disruption. The war ended with peace agreements, notably the Lomé Peace Accord in 1999, followed by disarmament and UN peacekeeping efforts, restoring stability in Sierra Leone.
